# Row Level Security (RLS) policies

In `create policy` statements, **never** use `auth.uid()` or `auth.jwt()` directly. Wrap them in a subquery so Postgres caches the result per statement:

- Use `(select auth.uid())` instead of `auth.uid()`
- Use `(select auth.jwt())` instead of `auth.jwt()`

Same for any other `auth.*()` or `current_setting()` used in policy expressions.

Example:

```sql
-- ❌ BAD — re-evaluated per row
create policy "..." on public.profiles for all using (auth.uid() = id);

-- ✅ GOOD — cached per statement
create policy "..." on public.profiles for all using ((select auth.uid()) = id);
```

Ref: https://supabase.com/docs/guides/database/postgres/row-level-security#call-functions-with-select
